<entry>
<author><name><![CDATA[tokumaru]]></name></author>
<updated>2006-02-04T13:20:57-07:00</updated>
<published>2006-02-04T13:20:57-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=1060&amp;p=9068#p9068</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=1060&amp;p=9068#p9068"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[tile replacement for movement]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=1060&amp;p=9068#p9068"><![CDATA[
I'd say you have to keep a variable that tells what the player is doing, and also defines the animation frame to use for it.<br /><br />Say you have 4 frames of animation for the character:<br />0 - standing;<br />1-3 - walking;<br /><br />The game would start with that variable at 0, with the player just standing there. You'll will check that variable every frame, and while it is 0 you'll jump to the part of the code that draws the guy standing.<br /><br />Then, when the player presses right, and there is no wall or anything in the way, you set that variable to the code of the first walking frame, wich is "1". That means the next time you read that variable, you'll jump to the part of the code that draws the guy in his first walking frame.<br /><br />Then, every frame (or every few frames, to have slower animation) you update that variable to the next walking frame. And set it back to 0 as soon as the player stops walking.<br /><br />The best thing to do is have the animation sync'ed with the player's speed, if you implemented such a thing yet. Have the delay between animation frames get smaller as the player moves faster.<br /><br />Well, that's it: have a variable to control what frame of animation to show, maintain/update it every frame as necessary and use it every frame to decide what to draw.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=95">tokumaru</a> — Sat Feb 04, 2006 1:20 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
