<author><name><![CDATA[Memblers]]></name></author>
<updated>2006-02-03T20:19:55-07:00</updated>
<published>2006-02-03T20:19:55-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=1060&amp;p=9054#p9054</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=1060&amp;p=9054#p9054"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: tile replacement for movement]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=1060&amp;p=9054#p9054"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle">lynxsolaris wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />Youre right.  It does seem that the variable is incrementing too fast.  I was<br />thinking (and tell me if Im wrong) about possibly doing some sort of<br />loop to was kill some time between steps. Would that be a correct way<br />of waiting a few frames?<br /></div><br /><br />Not a loop, because it would slow everything else down.  Do it all based on frames instead, with a fixed-point counter you can count frames and still get a high resolution (on average) since the counter wraps-around.<br /><br />Like this:<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">counter: .res 1<br />delay_value = 25 ; lower for more delay<br /><br /> lda counter<br /> clc<br /> adc #delay_value<br /> sta counter<br /> bcc skip<br /> inc isWalking<br />skip:<br /></div><br /><br />It's a good idea to use fixed-point numbers for sprite coordinates also.  So you can move less than a pixel per frame, and actually be moving.<br /><br />  <br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br /><div class="quotetitle">Memblers wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I wrote some animation code that works pretty well for me, I talked about the data format in this old thread here.<br /><a href="http://nesdev.com/bbs/viewtopic.php?t=493" class="postlink">http://nesdev.com/bbs/viewtopic.php?t=493</a><br /></div><br /><br />I looked over your code.   I guess I'm still too noob to understand <br />exactly whats going on without seeing how it interacts with the rest of<br />your code.  Is it possible for me to see it?<br /><br />Thnx.</div><br /><br />Here it is, I'm not sure how useful it is for anyone else, but it works great for me.<br /><a href="http://www.parodius.com/~memblers/nes/animate.asm" class="postlink">http://www.parodius.com/~memblers/nes/animate.asm</a><p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=10">Memblers</a> — Fri Feb 03, 2006 8:19 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
